    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Heat Before the Cold,'' by Terrence Joyce (Op-Ed, April 18), reminds us that the science of global warming and its scenarios for regional change offer two compelling extremes of climate change in the 21st century.</p>
        <p>Embedded in all of these warming and cooling scenarios is the reality of increased climate volatility.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Heat Before the Cold,'' by Terrence Joyce (Op-Ed, April 18), reminds us that the science of global warming and its scenarios for regional change offer two compelling extremes of climate change in the 21st century.</p>
        <p>Embedded in all of these warming and cooling scenarios is the reality of increased climate volatility.</p>
        <p>We can only imagine the impact of this increased volatility on agricultural productivity, on human settlements and on those planetary life-support systems on which we depend for human well-being.</p>
        <p>JOHN E. ISOM  Madison, Wis., April 18, 2002</p>
      </block>
